Date: Mon 20 Nov 2006
From: Joe Dudley <jdudley@eaicorp.com>
Source: The Australian [edited]
<http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,20867,20786753-23289,00.html>

Australia: infections rise in flu outbreak in Canberra
------------------------------------------------------
Health officials in Canberra suspect that another person has been
infected in an influenza outbreak which has swept through a nursing
home and already killed 6 elderly residents. The [lethal] strain has
infected 57 people, including at least 7 nursing home staff. Tests
were still being conducted yesterday [19 Nov 2006] to determine
whether the latest respiratory illness was part of the same strain
[outbreak], a spokeswoman for ACT (Australian Capital Territory)
health minister Katy Gallagher said.
The latest victim was a 90 year old man who passed away at the
Jindalee Nursing Home in Canberra's south on Thursday [16 Nov 2006]
night. Staff had notified authorities on 1 Nov 2006 that an unknown
illness had swept through the residence.
Health authorities have offered staff and residents of the home
anti-viral medication, including the drug Tamiflu (oseltamivir), and
have sought assistance from the Commonwealth. ACT acting chief health
officer Charles Guest reassured residents, staff, and their families
that the outbreak was not connected to pandemic influenza or the
deadly H5N1 virus, commonly known as bird flu, following analysis of
the virus.
The Australian Medical Association (AMA) yesterday [19 Nov 2006]
warned that Australia's pandemic management plan lacked consistency.
AMA president Mukesh Haikerwal said state governments had neglected
to share their pandemic plans with doctors, and there was a lack of
coordination across states and territories on the role of fever
clinics and how to direct patients to the most appropriate care.
"General practitioners are keen to properly prepare for a flu
pandemic but they're currently trying to do so in a vacuum of
information on how jurisdictions propose to mobilize, integrate,
finance and protect primary care," Dr Haikerwal said. Australia has
spent AUD 600 million [USD 462 million] since 2003 preparing for a
possible influenza outbreak.
[byline: Cath Hart]
