[2]
Date: Mon 20 Nov 2006
From: Matthew Mason <Matthew.Mason@brhs.com.au>
Source: ABC News online [edited]
<http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200611/s1792470.htm>

Australia: another suspected influenza case in Canberra nursing home
-----------------------------------------------
Health authorities are investigating another suspected case of
influenza that has already claimed 6 lives at the Jindalee nursing
home in Canberra. Acting chief health officer Charles Guest says 57
people have so far been infected with the flu and another suspected
case was uncovered at the weekend.
Dr Guest says staff and residents have been given anti-viral
medications. "We are investigating very actively at Jindalee and
other aged care facilities around Canberra at the moment to check
this influenza outbreak," he said.
--
Matt Mason
Infection Control Nurse
Bairnsdale Regional Health Service
<Matthew.Mason@brhs.com.au>
[The outbreak of respiratory illness at the Jindalee nursing home in
Canberra has now been attributed to an unspecified strain of human
(seasonal) influenza virus. Although this is an unusual time of year
for an epidemic of influenza in the southern hemisphere, nursing
homes caring for elderly and immunologically deficient patients are
particularly vulnerable to any respiratory virus infection at any
time of the year. Further information would be appreciated regarding
the serotype of the virus or viruses responsible for this outbreak. -
Mod.CP]
